[[Back to the shore|Carthage shore]]

:: Return the page [venue-cecilcourt] {"position":"500,1850","size":"100,100"}
You show him 93. O'Flatterly takes it, firmly and gently, then lays it into his papers, where it should be. He would shelve you, if he could, among his best books.

[['You don't know the good that you've done'|O'Flatterly's Gift]]

:: O'Flatterly's Gift [venue-cecilcourt] {"position":"500,1950","size":"100,100"}
<script>setTimeout(function(){ if (window.dssAudio) window.dssAudio.vialClink(); }, 700);</script>\
'If I may, let me give you small thanks.'

From beneath the counter he produces a small glass vial.

'This,' he says, 'is a slice of the liver of Percy Bysshe Shelley, the poet. It was cut from his body, as it burned on the beach at Viareggio, by his friend Trelawny, who mistook the liver for the heart. Swallow it if you ever get too close to the end.'
