Onstage there are three: Moe D'Alcousin on the saxophone, a pianist, and a guitarist.]

(if: $tookLily3 is false)[|lily3>[(display: "Lily SVG")]\
(click-replace: ?lily3)[(set: $lilyCount to $lilyCount + 1)(set: $tookLily3 to true)(display: "Lily SVG")<span class="lily-glimpse lily-fade">You've the sense, distinct and cordial, that Lily is sitting behind you, and will not look,</span>(if: $lilyHintShown is false)[(set: $lilyHintShown to true)<div class="lily-glimpse-hint">(Gather flowers. There are five to find.)</div>](if: $lilyCount is 5)[(set: $confidence to ($statGain: $confidence, 25))(set: $sobriety to ($statGain: $sobriety, 15))<div class="pent-reveal-note"><div class="pent-reveal-title">⛤ THE PENTACLE ⛤</div><div class="pent-reveal-body">Five flowers, five points; the city draws its star around you.</div><span class="inventory-note">&#9734; MORALE +25 | SOBRIETY +15</span></div><script>setTimeout(function(){if(window.dssRevealPentangleOnMap)window.dssRevealPentangleOnMap();},900);</script>]]](else:)[<div class="lily-taken">(display: "Lily SVG")</div>]

(link: "⟡ LORE: Ronnie Scott's ⟡")[<div class="lore-box">
You hear four stories about Ronnie Scotts and half of them are true.

1. My mother and father went one night in the eighties. No particular occasion and they didn't know who was playing. They sat behind the piano; too close for anyone who really wanted to hear it. Nina Simone played that night.

2. Ronnie once gave a pianist a fulsome introduction: Where he'd played and who with; where he'd seen him play and with whom; and nobody came on stage. The band loops twice round the head and still nobody's there. That's the best I've ever heard him, said Ronnie. He was never heard of again.

3. You know about the jam they do upstairs? One night my friend's friend was playing it; a physicist by trade and a brilliant jazz piano player. Partway through his turn someone whispers in his ear: There's a man in the stalls who will take a harmonic solo. The band turned the tune around then grew gentle to wait for him. He comes in: it's Stevie Wonder, it could be no other. I hear he's a very kind man.

4. A man was paying for a scotch when the horn started soloing. He finished his drink, put on his coat, his hat and stepped out into the cold Soho rain to see a woman, returning just as the horn seemed to finish her solo.
</div>]

There is a pianist with a long and sculpted face, like El Greco painted a heron, and a young guitarist who looks like he was groomed by Bruce Springsteen.

Says one: 'Lost boy, get us a drink.' You acquiesce.

'Bourbon.'

'A Moscow Mule.'

'Scotch.'

